# v1.93.0 — Guest feature rework (per-row + typed + positions)

Source brief: replace v1.91.0 `MatchdayGuestEntry` (single row per
(matchday, team) with `externalCount + leagueCount` integers) with
per-guest rows on a new `MatchdayGuest` model. Each guest gets a
`type` (EXTERNAL or LEAGUE), their own `positions[]`, and a
`displayOrder` for stable per-section ordering. UI swings from
two-number-input modal to a table-based modal with per-row position
multi-select, "+ Add row" buttons per section, and per-row delete.
Pitch + list views treat each `MatchdayGuest` as a pseudo-Player with
positions, so the 6-pass formation algorithm places guests with
chosen positions through passes 1–2b and guests without positions
through pass 2.5 (v1.89.1 back-most non-GK fill).

## M1 — Schema + migration

### Schema deltas (`prisma/schema.prisma`)

1. New `GuestType` enum next to `LeagueVisibility`:
   ```
   enum GuestType {
     EXTERNAL
     LEAGUE
   }
   ```
2. `MatchdayGuestEntry` model REPLACED by `MatchdayGuest`:
   - `id String @id @default(cuid())`
   - `gameWeekId String` (FK GameWeek, ON DELETE CASCADE)
   - `leagueTeamId String` (FK LeagueTeam, ON DELETE CASCADE)
   - `type GuestType`
   - `positions String[] @default([])` — chosen preferred positions for
     this guest at this matchday; codes per league's `ballType` vocab
     (12-code soccer or 4-code futsal), validated server-side at write.
   - `displayOrder Int @default(0)` — 0..N-1 per (gameWeekId, leagueTeamId, type)
     section; drives "Ext Guest 1 / 2 / 3" labels and stable modal-row
     ordering.
   - `createdById String?` (FK User, ON DELETE SET NULL — audit trail)
   - `createdAt DateTime @default(now())` + `updatedAt DateTime @updatedAt`
   - `@@index([gameWeekId, leagueTeamId, type])` — primary fast-filter for
     "all guests for this team's matchday, sectioned by type"
   - `@@index([gameWeekId])`, `@@index([leagueTeamId])` — single-leg indexes
     kept for cascade-delete scans (matches v1.91.0 shape).
3. Back-relation renames:
   - `User.authoredGuestEntries MatchdayGuestEntry[]` → `User.authoredGuests MatchdayGuest[]`
   - `LeagueTeam.guestEntries MatchdayGuestEntry[]` → `LeagueTeam.guests MatchdayGuest[]`
   - `GameWeek.guestEntries MatchdayGuestEntry[]` → `GameWeek.guests MatchdayGuest[]`
4. No `@@unique` constraint on the new model — multiple rows per (gameWeekId,
   leagueTeamId, type) by design (one row per guest). The replacement-by-set
   semantic in `setMatchdayGuests` doesn't rely on a unique key — it does
   `deleteMany` + `createMany` in one transaction.

### Migration SQL (`prisma/migrations/20260522000000_add_matchday_guest_rows_replace_counts/migration.sql`)

DDL generated via `prisma migrate diff --from-schema-datamodel <pre> --to-schema-datamodel <post> --script`
(offline; per `docs/migration-sql-lessons.md` rule — NEVER hand-author
migration SQL). Prisma's natural emit order is DROP OLD → CREATE NEW;
we reorder to CREATE NEW → INSERT BACKFILL → DROP OLD so the backfill
runs atomically inside the same migration. The DDL statements are
byte-for-byte what Prisma emitted; the only manual additions are:

1. Two `INSERT INTO "MatchdayGuest" SELECT … FROM "MatchdayGuestEntry" e
   CROSS JOIN LATERAL generate_series(1, e."externalCount") AS s(i) WHERE
   e."externalCount" > 0` statements (one for EXTERNAL, one for LEAGUE)
   — pure-data backfill (permitted exception per migration-sql-lessons.md).
2. The reordering itself — Prisma's DROP-then-CREATE becomes CREATE-then-
   INSERT-then-DROP. Reorder is necessary because the backfill reads from
   the old table and writes to the new one; both must exist at INSERT time.

### Why one migration, not two + script

The brief offered an escape hatch: "two migrations + backfill script"
for awkward CREATE+INSERT+DROP cases. We chose the one-migration path
because:
- Prod has zero `MatchdayGuestEntry` rows (v1.91.0 shipped 2026-05-10
  and no user submitted any guests before the redesign brief landed).
  The backfill is a no-op on prod.
- Non-prod environments (preview branches, dev DB) may have test rows.
  Inlining the backfill makes the migration self-sufficient — operator
  doesn't need to remember a script step on those environments.
- The backfill SQL uses Prisma-generated table + column names exactly
  ("MatchdayGuestEntry", "externalCount", "leagueCount", "createdById",
  "createdAt", "updatedAt") and Prisma-generated `MatchdayGuest` column
  names — no @@map slip risk (the post-mortem rule).
- `gen_random_uuid()` is a Postgres-13 built-in; Neon runs PG ≥15. No
  extension needed.

If prod had non-zero `MatchdayGuestEntry` rows the same migration still
works — the LATERAL generate_series expansion handles N rows correctly,
each yielding (externalCount + leagueCount) MatchdayGuest rows with
contiguous displayOrders (0..externalCount-1 for EXTERNAL, then
0..leagueCount-1 for LEAGUE).

### Migration verification

`prisma migrate diff` was run against the saved pre-edit schema
(`/tmp/schema-pre-v193.prisma`) and the new schema. The emitted DDL
(verified byte-for-byte against migration.sql) is:

```
-- CreateEnum
CREATE TYPE "GuestType" AS ENUM ('EXTERNAL', 'LEAGUE');

-- DropForeignKey
ALTER TABLE "MatchdayGuestEntry" DROP CONSTRAINT "MatchdayGuestEntry_gameWeekId_fkey";
ALTER TABLE "MatchdayGuestEntry" DROP CONSTRAINT "MatchdayGuestEntry_leagueTeamId_fkey";
ALTER TABLE "MatchdayGuestEntry" DROP CONSTRAINT "MatchdayGuestEntry_createdById_fkey";

-- DropTable
DROP TABLE "MatchdayGuestEntry";

-- CreateTable
CREATE TABLE "MatchdayGuest" (
    "id" TEXT NOT NULL,
    "gameWeekId" TEXT NOT NULL,
    "leagueTeamId" TEXT NOT NULL,
    "type" "GuestType" NOT NULL,
    "positions" TEXT[] DEFAULT ARRAY[]::TEXT[],
    "displayOrder" INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
    "createdById" TEXT,
    "createdAt" TIMESTAMP(3) NOT NULL DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    "updatedAt" TIMESTAMP(3) NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT "MatchdayGuest_pkey" PRIMARY KEY ("id")
);

-- CreateIndex
CREATE INDEX "MatchdayGuest_gameWeekId_leagueTeamId_type_idx" ON "MatchdayGuest"("gameWeekId", "leagueTeamId", "type");
CREATE INDEX "MatchdayGuest_gameWeekId_idx" ON "MatchdayGuest"("gameWeekId");
CREATE INDEX "MatchdayGuest_leagueTeamId_idx" ON "MatchdayGuest"("leagueTeamId");

-- AddForeignKey
ALTER TABLE "MatchdayGuest" ADD CONSTRAINT "MatchdayGuest_gameWeekId_fkey" FOREIGN KEY ("gameWeekId") REFERENCES "GameWeek"("id") ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE;
ALTER TABLE "MatchdayGuest" ADD CONSTRAINT "MatchdayGuest_leagueTeamId_fkey" FOREIGN KEY ("leagueTeamId") REFERENCES "LeagueTeam"("id") ON DELETE CASCADE ON UPDATE CASCADE;
ALTER TABLE "MatchdayGuest" ADD CONSTRAINT "MatchdayGuest_createdById_fkey" FOREIGN KEY ("createdById") REFERENCES "User"("id") ON DELETE SET NULL ON UPDATE CASCADE;
```

The two INSERT statements (between CREATE INDEX/FK and DROP CONSTRAINT/DROP TABLE
in the migration file) are NOT Prisma-emitted — they're the pure-data backfill.

## M2 — Server action setMatchdayGuests

- New `setMatchdayGuests({ leagueSlug, matchdayPublicId, teamPublicId, guests: { type, positions }[] })`
  in `src/app/api/guests/actions.ts`. The legacy `setMatchdayGuestEntry` is GONE
  (re-introducing it is a regression target in `tests/unit/v193_guest_rework.test.ts`).
- Replacement-by-set: `prisma.$transaction([deleteMany({gameWeekId, leagueTeamId}), createMany(rows)])`.
  The v1.91.0 upsert-by-key shape is replaced by set-replacement, which behaves identically from
  the caller's POV (submit new state, it overwrites the prior).
- Position validation per league `ballType` via `normalizePositions(raw, league.ballType)`. Soccer
  codes against a futsal league throw "Invalid position …" before any DB write.
- `displayOrder` re-derived server-side per type section (`externalCounter` / `leagueCounter`
  both starting at 0). The modal "delete row 2" path can therefore never leave persisted gaps;
  the client's submitted order is the new ordering, but the indices are owned server-side.
- Audit: `createdById = currentUserId` on EVERY created row. Every replacement re-stamps the
  audit trail (matches v1.91.0 "last submitter" semantic but now per-row).
- Auth: gate on `session.userId` OR `session.lineId` (v1.80.10 / v1.59.1 pattern). Admin-
  orthogonal — no `session.isAdmin` reference (v1.67.0 standing rule).
- Cap: `MAX_GUESTS_PER_TEAM = 50` (same as the per-field cap in v1.91.0).
- Revalidate `domain: 'public'` with the same 5-path list as v1.91.0.

`dbToPublicLeagueData` swung from `prisma.matchdayGuestEntry.findMany` to
`prisma.matchdayGuest.findMany` with `orderBy: [{ type: 'asc' }, { displayOrder: 'asc' }]`,
yielding the new `MatchdayGuests` shape (`{ [matchdayId]: { [teamId]: MatchdayGuestEntry[] } }`).
The empty-result shape carries `guests: {}` (replaces v1.91.0 `guestCounts: {}`).

Type renames threaded through `Dashboard`, `ClassicLeagueHomepage`, `MultiLeagueHub`, and the
three page.tsx routes (`/`, `/id/[slug]`, `/id/[slug]/md/[id]`).

## M3 — Modal UI rebuilt as a table

`AddGuestsModal.tsx` fully rewritten. Top-level component owns `rows: RowState[]` (each row has
`{ key, type, positions[] }`). Two `<GuestSection>` sub-components rendered in fixed order:

1. **League Guests** — type=LEAGUE, label prefix "League Guest", empty state "No league guests yet."
2. **External Guests** — type=EXTERNAL, label prefix "Ext Guest", empty state "No external guests yet."

Each section renders:
- Title + per-section row count + hint text.
- `<ul>` of rows. Each row shows `[Label "Ext Guest N" | trash button]` + `<PositionMultiSelect>`
  (chip-based, per league `ballType` vocab from `getPositionVocabulary(ballType)`).
- "+ Add row" button at the bottom; disabled when total rows would exceed 50.

Numbering ("Ext Guest 1", "Ext Guest 2", …) is computed from `index + 1` within each section;
purely presentational, since server re-derives `displayOrder` on submit. Order of rows in
modal is preserved on save (LEAGUE first, then EXTERNAL).

Modal contract mirrors `ApplyToLeagueModal` / `SignInLightbox`: portal, role=dialog,
aria-modal, ESC dismiss, backdrop dismiss, body-scroll-lock. New addition: outer
`overflow-y-auto` + `items-start sm:items-center` so a 50-row modal scrolls naturally on
mobile (the v1.91.0 modal had no scroll because it had a fixed 2-input footprint).

Title reads `Guests for ${teamName}` per the brief.

Lazy-load wiring in `MatchdayAvailability.tsx` unchanged (still `next/dynamic` so the modal
chunk only loads on first click — perf carryover from v1.80.8).

## M4 — Pitch + list view + going count

**Pitch view.** `synthesizeGuestPlayers` signature changed from `(teamId, count: number)` to
`(teamId, guests: MatchdayGuestEntry[])`. Each MatchdayGuest row becomes one pseudo-Player:

```ts
{
  id: 'guest-' + sourceRow.id,             // NEW prefix (was 'guest-pseudo-')
  name: 'Ext Guest N' | 'League Guest N',  // displayOrder + 1, per type
  teamId,
  position: positions.join('/') || null,    // joined string for legacy reader compat
  preferredPositions: positions,
  secondaryPositions: [],
  picture: null,
  image: null,
  retiredAt: null,
}
```

The `preferredPositions` field is the load-bearing change: the v1.85.2 5-pass formation
algorithm (and v1.89.1's pass 2.5 follow-on) places guests with declared positions through
passes 1a/1b/2a/2b just like real players. Guests with `positions: []` fall through to
pass 2.5 (back-most non-GK fill; GK hard-excluded). Pinned by:

- `guest with positions=[CB] takes a CB slot via pass 1a` — assignPlayersToFormation
  test in `v193_guest_rework.test.ts`.
- `guest with positions=[] falls through to pass 2.5 (back-most non-GK)` — same file.
- `multiple positionless guests still never land at GK (v1.89.1 hard rule)` — same file.

`FormationPitch.tsx#playersWithoutPositions` filter still excludes guest pseudo-IDs via
`!isGuestPseudoId(p.id)` — the new "guest-" prefix matches the same predicate, so the
"fill in your profile" hint stays suppressed for guests even when their positions[] is empty.

**List view.** Single v1.91.0 `'GUEST'` bucket replaced by two sub-buckets:
- `'LEAGUE_GUEST'` (rendered first per brief)
- `'EXTERNAL_GUEST'` (second)

`BUCKET_ORDER` becomes `['GK', 'DF', 'MF', 'FW', 'UNB', 'LEAGUE_GUEST', 'EXTERNAL_GUEST']`.
Bucket type derived per-player via `guestTypeOf(p)`, which inspects the synthesised name
prefix ("League Guest" / "Ext Guest"). `synthesizeGuestPlayers` is the only writer of guest
pseudo-Players, so the convention is authoritative.

Within each guest sub-bucket, the sort is `localeCompare(b.name, undefined, { numeric: true })`
so "Ext Guest 10" comes after "Ext Guest 2" (not lex-sorted "10, 2, 3, …").

Guest pills now render the joined position string (or "Any" for empty positions) instead of
the v1.91.0 hardcoded "GUEST" label. Pill colouring stays neutral (no auth-linked User → no
role-coloured pill); only avatar (Player.image) is suppressed for guests.

**Going count.** Unchanged from v1.91.0 — `confirmedIds = [...goingIds, ...guestIds]` and
`total = confirmedIds.length`. The new shape feeds the same length-based aggregation.

